          "title": "The longing for salvation from Zion (53:6)",
          "body": "The Psalm ends not with a statement but with a longing — 'Oh, that the salvation of Israel would come out of Zion!' The optative construction (mi-yitten in Hebrew, literally 'who will give?') is the standard Hebrew expression of deep, unfulfilled desire. At the moment of writing, the salvation has not come. The indictment of verses 1-3 stands. The predation of verse 4 continues. The pattern of judgment in verse 5 has been seen in the past but is not yet the final word. So the Psalm does not end in arrival but in yearning.\n\nThe content of the longing is precise: 'When God restores His captive people, let Jacob rejoice, let Israel be glad.' Shevut — the turning of captivity — is the great reversal the prophets promised. Isaiah 52:7-10, Jeremiah 29:14, and Zephaniah 3:20 all use the same language for the definitive eschatological restoration. The parallelism of Jacob / Israel and rejoice (gil) / be glad (samach) returns to the corporate identity of the covenant community — they will exult together, as the indictment fell on them together.\n\nYeshuah (salvation) is the Psalm's final theological word — and the word from which Joshua, and ultimately Jesus, derive. The NT writers read this verse through the lens of what has come out of Zion in the person of Christ: the salvation the Psalm longed for has appeared in the incarnate, crucified, and risen Lord. Paul's quotation of Psalm 53 in Romans 3 places the indictment directly before the announcement of the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ (Romans 3:21-22) — making the Psalm's structure the structure of the gospel itself: universal condemnation (53:1-4), the pattern of God's judgment on the enemy of His people (53:5), and the longed-for salvation that finally comes out of Zion (53:6; cf. Romans 11:26)."
