        "body": "Verse 4 shifts the Psalm's angle of vision from the universal (all of humanity) to the specific: the 'workers of wickedness' (paal aven — those who practice iniquity as their vocation) and their treatment of God's people. The rhetorical question — 'Have they no knowledge?' — is God's own voice breaking into the Psalm. The question is not a request for information; it is an indictment framed as a question. They should know that devouring God's people is an act that will meet with divine response; their failure to know this is the evidence of their God-forgetfulness.\n\nThe comparison 'who eat up My people as though they ate bread' is the Psalm's most brutal image. The wicked consume the covenant community not in fury or passion but in casualness — as one eats bread. This is routine predation, the exploitation of the vulnerable by the powerful made into a daily habit. The image recurs in Micah 3:3 (rulers who 'eat the flesh of My people') and in the prophetic literature addressing economic oppression of the poor within Israel. The workers of wickedness are not foreign armies here; they are those within or adjacent to the community who systematically exploit it.\n\nThe third charge — 'and have not called upon God' — is the diagnostic center. To call upon God (qara) is the act that defines the worshiper in the Psalter (Psalm 4:1; 55:16; 86:5). Its absence defines the wicked with equal precision. They do not call upon God because they have denied God (53:1); and because they have denied God, they exploit His people without conscience. The three charges form a single portrait: willful ignorance, casual predation, prayerlessness. They are not three separate sins but three facets of the one sin of practical atheism in full social expression.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Paal aven* — workers of iniquity; paal emphasizes the doing, the production, the craft of wickedness — these are skilled practitioners. *Akhal* (devour, eat) appears twice in the Hebrew of v.4 — the comparison uses the same verb for both eating people and eating bread. *Qara el-Elohim* — to call upon God; the covenantal prayer-term whose absence here marks the complete absence of a vertical relationship."
