        "excerpt": "There they were in great fear where no fear had been; for God scattered the bones of him who encamped against you; you put them to shame, because God had rejected them.",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the Psalm's pivot from diagnosis to demonstration. Everything in verses 1-4 has been analytical — what the fool says, what God sees, what the wicked do. Verse 5 is narrative: something happened. The triple pachad (fear/dread) in the Hebrew is the alarm bell. 'There they were overwhelmed with dread, with dread to fear' — the piling of the same root three times is a poetic enactment of the panic itself: the terror is so total that the language breaks open in repetition.\n\nThe location is critical: 'where no fear had been.' The wicked had established a posture of security precisely at the point of their aggression against God's people. The encampment against God's people was, from the enemy's perspective, an act of confident power. God's response is to make that place of confident power the place of annihilating terror. This is the theological irony the Psalm has been building toward: the fool who says 'there is no God' does not make God absent; he simply delays his encounter with the God who is present until the encounter is catastrophic.\n\nThe verse has been read as referring to Sennacherib's siege of Jerusalem (2 Kings 19:35 — 185,000 Assyrian soldiers dead in a night) by a number of patristic and Reformed commentators, including Calvin, who notes the 'scattering of bones' as particularly apt for an army suddenly destroyed without battle. But the Psalm does not name the event, and the lack of specificity is likely deliberate: the verse presents a pattern, not an annotation. Wherever the wicked have encamped against God's people, God has scattered. The specific fulfillments — Pharaoh at the Red Sea, Sennacherib at Jerusalem, Haman's gallows — all illustrate the same theological grammar.\n\nThe verse closes with 'God had rejected them' (maas — to despise, to refuse, to remove favor). The same verb is used of God's rejection of Saul (1 Samuel 15:23, 26) and of the sacrifices of the disobedient (Isaiah 1:14). The rejection is covenantal: God has removed from the wicked any claim on His protection, mercy, or favor. They stood against His people; He stood against them.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pachad* (×3) — the repetition is unique in the Psalter and deliberately overwhelming. *Pazar* (scattered) — to spread abroad, disperse; used of God's scattering enemies in Psalm 68:1 ('Let God arise, let His enemies be scattered'). *Maas* (rejected, despised) — the covenantal term for removal of divine favor, the opposite of *chanan* (gracious acceptance)."
