        "title": "The longing that becomes messianic promise",
        "range": "53:6",
        "excerpt": "Oh, that the salvation of Israel would come out of Zion! When God restores His captive people, Let Jacob rejoice, let Israel be glad.",
        "body": "The Psalm's final verse is one of the Old Testament's most compressed expressions of eschatological hope. After five verses of indictment and judgment, the Psalm refuses to end there. Instead it pivots on the optative construction — 'Oh, that' — the Hebrew expression of unfulfilled but burning desire. The salvation of Israel has not yet come. The captivity is not yet restored. The longing is not wishful thinking; it is theologically grounded desire anchored in what the Psalm has already demonstrated: God sees, God investigates, God judges the enemies of His people, and God is the source of salvation.\n\nThe content of the longing is twofold. First, yeshuah out of Zion — salvation proceeding from the place of God's covenantal dwelling. This is not nationalism but covenant theology: the One who dwells in Zion is the One who saves, and His salvation moves outward from His presence. Isaiah 2:3 makes the same directional claim: 'The law will go forth from Zion, and the word of the LORD from Jerusalem.' Zion is not a city so much as the location of the divine presence in covenant with His people. Second, the restoration of shevut — the turning of captivity. The term appears at the great turning points of Israel's history: Deuteronomy 30:3 (Moses' promise of restoration after exile), Jeremiah 29:14 (God's promise to those in Babylon), and Psalm 126:4 (the post-exilic community's own prayer using the same phrase).\n\nThe NT reads this verse through the lens of the resurrection. Paul's use of Psalm 53 in Romans 3 frames the indictment precisely in order to announce the yeshuah that has come in Christ. Romans 11:26 — 'The Deliverer will come from Zion' — is a direct quotation of Isaiah 59:20 but is embedded in a canonical argument that includes the Psalter's Zion-salvation hope. The salvation the Psalm longed for has appeared: out of Zion in the person of the incarnate Son. The 'captive people' whom God restores are not only national Israel but the full people of God, who were held captive to sin and death (cf. Isaiah 61:1; Luke 4:18). Jacob's rejoicing and Israel's gladness are the language of eschatological celebration — the register of the New Jerusalem (Revelation 21:3-4).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mi-yitten* (Oh, that) — literally 'who will give?' — the standard Hebrew optative of deep longing. *Yeshuah* — salvation, deliverance, the root of Joshua (*Yehoshua*) and Jesus (*Yeshua*). *Shevut* (captivity/restoration) — the great reversal term of the prophetic tradition. *Gil* (rejoice) and *samach* (be glad) — the twin verbs of eschatological celebration in the Psalter and prophets (cf. Isaiah 25:9; Zechariah 9:9)."
